<p>A U.S. guided-missile destroyer, the USS Gravely, docked in Port of Spain, Trinidad and Tobago, on Sunday to take part in joint training with local forces as Washington says it is intensifying operations against drug trafficking near Venezuela . The movement comes as the aircraft carrier USS Gerald R. Ford was reported moving closer to Venezuela, part of a broader U.S. military buildup the administration says targets narcotics networks and &quot;narco-terrorists&quot; . Venezuela condemned the exercises as a provocation and accused Trinidad and the U.S. Central Intelligence Agency of hostile acts, escalating diplomatic tensions in the region .</p><img src='https://kagiproxy.com/img/E441sRoHf5rvv80elf0BPyg36bCXD0ZmQA1LbHy7vYhd88rflg2dIKjDkGSB52oHLZGV__K_v55e5UrtCqX4ASQ_arqbyeSfp3wgEt7b' alt='The USS Gravely warship is seen at a distance off the coast of Port of Spain, the capital of Trinidad and Tobago.' /><br /><h3>Highlights:</h3><ul><li>Carrier movement: The Pentagon ordered the deployment of the aircraft carrier USS Gerald R. Ford toward the Caribbean, intensifying the naval presence near Venezuela .</li><li>Maritime strikes: U.S. forces have conducted maritime strikes destroying at least 10 boats, an operation that sources say killed at least 43 people, according to reporting on the campaign against suspected drug traffickers .</li><li>Host nation role: Trinidad and Tobago announced the Gravely&#x27;s arrival and said U.S. Marines will conduct joint training with local defence forces during the ship&#x27;s stay .</li><li>Venezuelan accusations: Venezuelan officials, including Vice President Delcy Rodríguez, accused Trinidad and Tobago and the U.S. CIA of carrying out a &#x27;military provocation&#x27; amid joint exercises .</li></ul><blockquote>A new eternal war - President Nicolás Maduro</blockquote><h3>Perspectives:</h3><ul><li>United States government (administration): U.S. officials describe the deployment as part of a campaign against drug-trafficking organisations and so-called &#x27;narco-terrorists&#x27; operating in international waters. (<a href='https://www.npr.org/2025/10/27/nx-s1-5585100/venezuela-prepares-for-potential-land-strikes-as-u-s-builds-up-military-in-caribbean'>NPR</a>)</li><li>Venezuelan government: Venezuela condemned the joint exercises as a military provocation and accused Trinidad and the U.S. CIA of hostile actions. (<a href='https://www.reuters.com/world/americas/venezuela-condemns-military-provocation-by-cia-trinidad-tobago-2025-10-26/'>Reuters</a>)</li><li>Trinidad and Tobago government: Port of Spain announced the Gravely&#x27;s arrival and confirmed planned joint training with U.S. Marines during the ship&#x27;s stay. (<a href='https://www.dawn.com/news/1951491/us-warship-arrives-in-trinidad-and-tobago'>Dawn</a>)</li><li>U.S. Senate (Sen. Lindsey Graham): Lawmakers warned that land strikes in Venezuela are a &#x27;real possibility&#x27; amid rising tensions. (<a href='https://www.cbsnews.com/news/us-warship-docks-trinidad-and-tobago-venezuela/'>CBS News</a>)</li></ul><h3>Sources:</h3><ul><li><a href='https://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/us-warship-docks-trinidad-tobago-puts-pressure-venezuela-126880667'>US warship docks in Trinidad and Tobago, puts more pressure on Venezuela</a> - abcnews.go.com</li><li><a href='https://www.scmp.com/news/world/americas/article/3330406/us-warship-docks-trinidad-and-tobago-putting-more-pressure-venezuela'>US destroyer docks in Trinidad and Tobago, upping pressure on Venezuela</a> - scmp.com</li><li><a href='https://www.straitstimes.com/world/venezuela-condemns-military-provocation-by-cia-and-trinidad-and-tobago'>Venezuela condemns ‘military provocation’ by CIA and Trinidad and Tobago</a> - straitstimes.com</li><li><a href='https://www.boston.com/news/politics/2025/10/26/us-warship-docks-in-trinidad-and-tobago-putting-more-pressure-on-venezuela/'>US warship docks in Trinidad and Tobago, putting more pressure on Venezuela</a> - boston.com</li><li